children.text: There are roof trusses that have been installed with a large bow, outside the maximum allowable tolerances documented in the standards.
The truss manufacturer’s erection tolerances, and the relevant Australian Standard, AS 4440 Installation of Nail-Plated Timber Roof Trusses, states that

‘Tolerance is critical for both a good roof line and effective bracing. Trusses to be erected with minimal bow, in the truss and in any chord, with a tolerance not exceeding the lesser of L/200 and 50mm, where L is as defined as shown in diagrams’ ;

These trusses must be properly straightened back to within the Australian Standards and manufacturer’s allowable erection tolerances otherwise they may possibly fail. Alternatively, the builder should provide the owner with documentation from the manufacturer to confirm that the current installation is acceptable.
